context: The word "paper" is etymologically derived from <b5_0>Latin papyrus<b5_0/>, which comes from the <a1_0><b11_0>Greek<b11_0/><a1_0/> πάπυρος (<b6_0>papuros<b6_0/>), the word for the <a3_0>Cyperus<a3_0/> papyrus plant. <a0_0><b10_0>Papyrus<b10_0/><a0_0/> is a thick, paper-like material produced from <a4_0>the <b13_0>pith<b13_0/><a4_0/> of the Cyperus papyrus plant, which was used in ancient Egypt and other Mediterranean cultures for writing before the introduction of paper into the Middle East and Europe. Although the word paper is etymologically derived from <b7_0>papyrus<b7_0/>, the two are produced very differently and the development of the first is distinct from the development of the second. Papyrus is a <b9_0>lamination of natural plant fibres<b9_0/>, while paper is manufactured from <b8_0>fibres whose properties have been changed by <a2_0><b12_0>maceration<b12_0/><a2_0/>.
